  {
    question: "What areas of my vehicle can be covered with PPF?",
    answer:
      "PPF can be applied to virtually any exterior painted surface of your vehicle. Our packages range from partial coverage focusing on high-impact areas (front bumper, hood, mirrors, door edges) to full vehicle protection. Common areas for PPF application include the full hood, fenders, front bumper, headlights, side mirrors, door cups and edges, rocker panels, A-pillars, rear bumper, and trunk ledge. For maximum protection, we offer complete vehicle wraps that shield every painted surface including the roof, doors, and quarter panels. We customize coverage based on your driving habits, vehicle usage, and budget considerations.",
  },
  {
    question: "How long does PPF last?",
    answer:
      "Our premium PPF products carry a 10-year manufacturer's warranty against yellowing, cracking, or peeling under normal use conditions. The actual lifespan depends on environmental factors, driving conditions, and maintenance practices. In typical driving conditions, you can expect 5-10 years of protection while maintaining clarity and protective properties. Unlike older generation films, modern premium PPF resists staining and yellowing even with prolonged sun exposure. The self-healing properties remain effective throughout the film's lifespan, continuing to eliminate minor scratches with heat exposure from the sun or warm water.",
  },
  {
    question: "How is PPF different from ceramic coatings?",
    answer:
      "PPF and ceramic coatings serve different protective purposes and can be complementary. PPF provides physical protection against rock chips, scratches, and physical impacts by absorbing the damage itself. It's a thicker, tangible layer (typically 6-8 mil thick) that can take a hit without damaging the paint underneath. Ceramic coatings, by contrast, are liquid polymer applications that create a chemical bond with the paint surface, offering enhanced gloss and protection against chemical contaminants, UV rays, and minor scratches. Ceramic coatings make cleaning easier but don't provide significant protection against physical impacts. For ultimate protection, many clients choose PPF for high-impact areas with a ceramic coating applied over the PPF and remaining painted surfaces.",
  },
  {
    question: "Does PPF change the appearance of my vehicle?",
    answer:
      "When professionally installed, premium PPF is virtually invisible. Modern high-quality films feature exceptional optical clarity that preserves the original appearance of your paint. Some PPF products even enhance the depth and gloss of your vehicle's finish. There might be subtle differences in texture on close inspection, and very sharp eyes might notice the film edges on partial installations, though our precision cutting and installation techniques minimize these visual cues. For those seeking visual enhancement, we also offer PPF with matte finishes that can transform the appearance of glossy paint to a sophisticated satin look while providing the same protective benefits.",
